[2]
Date: Tue 7 Mar 2017
Source: ABC (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) News [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-03-07/anthrax-outbreak-kills-80-cattle-on-queensland-grazing-property/8333256


About 80 cattle have died in an anthrax outbreak on a grazing property at St George in Queensland's southern inland. Biosecurity Queensland is working with managers at the property, where a biosecurity order is limiting movement in and out of the site. Chief biosecurity officer Dr Jim Thompson said tests detected the bacteria that cause anthrax.

He described anthrax as a naturally occurring bacterium that arises sporadically in Australia, with a small number of cases each year. "The last incidence of anthrax in Queensland, which occurred in 2002, was successfully contained," Dr Thompson said. "In this latest case, the property owner reported that approximately 80 cattle had died in a short period of time. A veterinarian attending the property on [Fri 3 Mar 2017] took samples from the dead animals in accordance with protocol and sent them to Biosecurity Queensland for testing.

"We commend the veterinarian and property owner for their quick response that will assist us in minimising the risk to the local industry. We have put in place biosecurity orders to restrict the movement of people, stock, and vehicles on and off the infected property, and will commence a vaccination program for the remaining cattle and a disposal and decontamination program for the deceased animals. It's believed the cattle deaths were caused by the disturbance of contaminated soil, followed by rainfall that distributed the soil containing the bacteria."

Queensland chief health officer Dr Jeannette Young said the risk of human exposure to anthrax from animals was generally regarded as very low. "Public health authorities are in contact with people on the property and the veterinarian," she said. "The veterinarian used appropriate personal protective equipment and 8 people, including family and a farm worker, did not have any contact with the dead animals."

Dr Thompson said all stock were vulnerable but it was not a contagious disease, like a virus. "It can affect humans, people have to be very careful around sick animals or those that have died from anthrax, we need to dispose of the carcass and decontaminate those areas," he said.

There has been another confirmed case of anthrax in Victoria in recent days, which caused the death of several sheep, but Dr Thompson said this was a coincidence. He said outbreaks usually occurred in what was known as the anthrax belt, which was linked to old stock routes where the animals were just left after they died. Dr Thompson said the only treatment was prevention by vaccination, but this was not normal practice because the disease was [now] so rare.

