communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Maps of Australia can be seen at http://www.ezilon.com/maps/images/oceania/australia-political-map.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4885298,58713. For a map showing the location of the outbreak in western Queensland, go to https://goo.gl/bmWKTl.

It is logical that this outbreak might have been initiated by soil disturbance of a 2002 anthrax cattle burial site. From experience we know that such cattle graves have a sunken surface at the top and that this natural basin will collect rainwater. To have 80 head affected in a very short time suggests that this water was drunk by, say, 10 cows; they died; and provided enough blood, whether from the ground by extravasation to be licked and tasted or to haemophagic tabanid flies from biting moribund or dead cows, feed, and then infect further cows. When the last Queensland outbreaks were in 2002 it is understandable that vaccination had abated in the past 14+ years without an outbreak. And responses tended to be slower as more recent herd problems present themselves as possible causes.

When dealing with anthrax carcasses make sure you are wearing rubber boots, disposable plastic gloves, and heavy duty paper overalls. When you take the overalls off, they can be tossed onto the burning carcasses; spouses object to such bloody dirty clothing going through the domestic washing machine. There is something to be said for wearing plastic bags over your boots as it greatly eases removing any bloody soil. The bags should also go into the fire along with the gloves.

Also, unless one is dealing with just one or 2 dead cows, it is wise to inform the adjoining cattle stations so that they can initiate vaccinating their stock as soon as possible. Sterne vaccine is very cheap, just pennies per dose, and even one case prevented has a high benefit cost ratio.

This cattle station is in the traditional anthrax area for eastern Australia and included in the GARP niche model map discussed in ProMED-mail postings: Anthrax - Australia: (VI) ovine, human exp 20170306.4882640 and Anthrax - Australia: niche modeling of historic distribution 20160622.4302780. - Mod.MHJ]
